Compressing A PNG image.
pngcrush -ow image.png

Compressing all PNG images whose name contains "223 - Average 1" and end by ".png".
for file in "223 - Average 1"*.png; do pngcrush -ow "$file"; done

Compressing all MP4 videos whose name begins by "75".
find . -maxdepth 1 -type f -name '75*.mp4'  -exec sh -c 'ffmpeg -y -i "$1" -c:v libx264 -crf 23 -c:a aac -b:a 128k "${1%.mp4}_compressed.mp4"' sh {} \;

Compressing all PNG images whose size is greater than 16 Mo.
find . -maxdepth 1 -type f -name '*.png' -size +16M -exec pngcrush -ow {} \;

Deleting all files in a folder (subfolders included).
find . -type f -delete

Deleting files whose name contains "Tolerance 1".
rm *"Tolerance 1"*

Getting the number of frames in the file "video"
ffprobe -v error -count_frames -select_streams v:0 -show_entries stream=nb_read_frames -of csv=p=0 video.mp4

Listing the subfolders of "Input" and "Output"
for dir in Input Output; do echo "=== $dir ==="; tree -d "$dir"; echo; done

Listing files whose name begis by 623 and contains "rage 0" and " 1.00-" | Display the number of files.
find . -type f -name "623*rage 0* 1.00-*" | awk '{print; c++} END{print c " files"}'

Listing unique filenames by cutting after ".jpg". 
find -type f   -printf '%f\n' | sed 's/ *.jpg//' | sort -u

Listing unique filename, in the "One Color" folder. Delete "Output/One Color" to run in the current folder. 
find . -type f -name "One color/543*" | sed 's/png.*//' | sort -u | awk '{print; c++} END{print c " files"}'
The path get cleaned and deduplicated and finally the number of lines produced displays.
Command options : 
sed 's/png.*//' 
  | Cutting after "png". For each line (file path), the first occurrence of the string “png” followed by any character (.*) is replaced with nothing. In concrete terms, as soon as it encounters "png" in the path, it truncates the line at that point, removing "png" and everything that follows on the line.
sort -u 
  | Sorting the lines in lexicographical order and removing duplicates (option -u).
awk '{print; c++} END{print c " files"}' 
  | Displaying, for each input line, the line (print) and increments the counter c. At the end (END), displays the total number of lines processed, in the form N files.

Listing the 20 largest JPG and PNG files (useful to launch in the "Output" folder if processing time is getting important).
find . -type f \( -iname '*.jpg' -o -iname '*.png' \) -exec du -h {} + | sort -hr | head -n 20

Listing MP4 files, including subfolders
find . -type f \( -iname "*.mp4" \) -printf "%P\n"

Renaming all files whose name begin by "ABC-" to replace it by "CBA".
for f in ABC-*; do
  mv "$f" "CBA-${f#ABC-}"
done

Renaming all files whose name begin by "ABC-" to delete the first 4 characters ("ABC-" is for the example).
for f in "ABC-"*; do   mv "$f" "${f#ABC-}"; done
